      <h1 style="font-size:2rem;line-height:1.35;">China Approves World's First Commercial Brain-Computer Interface Chip</h1>
      <div class="article-meta">
        <span>2026-05-12</span>
        <span class="separator">·</span>
        <span>Connie Wu</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="article-content">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:720px;">
      <p>On May 11, Nature reported a milestone: China approved the world's first commercial brain-computer interface (BCI) device for treating paralysis. Scientific American, Reuters, Bloomberg, Fierce Biotech, and Smithsonian Magazine all followed up.</p>
      <p>This is not a "China's Neuralink" story.</p>

      <h2>What happened</h2>
      <p>China's NMPA approved a device called NEO — a BCI implant for paralysis treatment. This marks the first time any regulator has approved a BCI device for commercial use, not clinical trials. Neuralink, by comparison, remains under the FDA's clinical trial framework.</p>
      <p class="footnote">Source: Nature, Reuters, Bloomberg, Scientific American, 2026.5</p>

      <h2>Two technological paths</h2>
      <p>Neuralink uses intracortical implantation — electrodes inserted directly into brain tissue. High precision, but highly invasive.</p>
      <p>China's NEO follows an endovascular route — electrodes are delivered through the jugular vein to brain blood vessels, sitting against the cortex without penetrating. Lower surgical risk, no craniotomy needed.</p>
      <p>These are fundamentally different approaches, not directly comparable.</p>
      <p class="footnote">Source: Scientific American, 2026.5</p>

      <h2>Signals of an accelerating field</h2>
      <p>China's BCI activity goes beyond this single approval. 36Kr reports that Chinese BCI companies raised 3.8 billion yuan in Q1 2026 — exceeding the entire 2025 total. Investment logic is shifting from "concept hype" to "industrialization expectations."</p>
      <p>Meanwhile, Mass General Brigham and Brown University published research showing two paralyzed patients able to type thoughts using a BCI — published in Nature during the same week.</p>
      <p>Smithsonian Magazine's headline captured it: "An Experimental Brain Implant Allows People With Paralysis to Type Their Thoughts With Their Minds."</p>
      <p>Neuralink is also pushing forward. Elon Musk recently stated Neuralink plans high-volume BCI production by 2026.</p>
      <p class="footnote">Sources: 36Kr; Nature; Mass General Brigham; statnews; Smithsonian Magazine; Reuters</p>

      <h2>Why this matters</h2>

      <h3>Diverging regulatory paths</h3>
      <p>China's NMPA approved for commercial use; the FDA is still in clinical trials. Each regulatory framework follows its own logic. How these frameworks diverge will shape BCI product timelines globally.</p>

      <h3>BCI transitions from academia to industry</h3>
      <p>The 3.8 billion yuan Q1 figure signals a shift. Global BCI market projections for 2036 reach tens of billions of dollars.</p>

      <h3>Imagination for human-AI fusion</h3>
      <p>BCI isn't about "replacing" human brains. Paralyzed patients typing with their thoughts — this is the most direct and urgent human-AI extension scenario.</p>
      <p>The more interesting question isn't "who leads the BCI race" but: who sets the rules for this market when BCI becomes a commercial product?</p>

